[2] Eastern Europe: H1N1 increase in cases
Date: Thu 21 Jan 2016
Source: Euronews [edited]
http://www.euronews.com/2016/01/21/eighteen-people-die-in-armenia-three-in-georgia-from-h1n1-swine-flu


Influenza (H1N1) in eastern Europe claiming lives, many cases in hospital
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
H1N1 swine flu: a new pandemic on the way?
------------------------------------------
An outbreak of swine flu in eastern Europe is claiming lives and causing a stir in the media. A major H1N1 outbreak sparked a World Health Organization pandemic alert in June 2009, after the virus emerged from Mexico and the United States. The outbreak killed around 18 500 people in 214 countries. The alert was lifted in August 2010. Since then bird flu has become a pressing preoccupation, but swine flu has the potential to be a global killer. So should we be worried?

Armenia has reported 18 deaths, with neighbouring Georgia 3, but both countries say the victims had complications and sought treatment far too late, and there is no question of an epidemic.

In Russia at least 17 people have died and hundreds have been hospitalised, and Ukraine says there have been 50 deaths there, with the flu virus especially rampant in the Russian-occupied east of the country.

Iran says the virus is also claiming lives there in the country's 1st ever large outbreak of the H1N1 strain. At least 112 people have died, concentrated in the south east of the country.

The health authorities in India have embarked on a big public awareness campaign following a 2nd death from the disease. Swine flu is of special concern in India, with its dense urban populations and poor sanitation.

Of course seasonal influenza occurs every year and the viruses change each year, and many people have some immunity to the circulating virus that helps limit infections. Some countries also use seasonal influenza vaccines to reduce illness and deaths.

By contrast, the H1N1 was a new virus when it emerged and most people had no or little immunity to it, giving it pandemic potential. One of the lessons from history is that influenza pandemics can kill millions, and there was no pandemic influenza vaccine at the outset.

Now H1N1 treatments have been developed but their effectiveness has been questioned, hence the media panic at any sign that it may be making a comeback. If you think you may be at risk, or want to know more about the disease, the World Health Organization has prepared a factsheet [http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/frequently_asked_questions/about_disease/en/].

[byline: Robert Hackwill]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A reminder that "swine" flu is actually seasonal flu that is transmitted from person to person as easily as the normal seasonal flu and can be passed among people by exposure to infected droplets expelled by coughing or sneezing. These droplets are inhaled, or alternatively may contaminate hands or surfaces. Most countries in the world have confirmed infections from H1N1.

Unlike typical seasonal flu patterns, this virus causes high levels of summer infections in the northern hemisphere, and then even higher levels of activity during cooler months in this part of the world. The majority of people with pandemic influenza experience mild illness and recover fully without treatment.

A map showing eastern Europe can be accessed at https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?mid=zqh6TmzOjEbs.kwLYxEHV9x7g&hl=en. - Mod.LK

